{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129625909,"sessionID":"ses_18801b231ffe1T23Rry15kpUZw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_00_80KWyOxN9URlkSGFxSna8711","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: deep-agent-improvement\n3: description: \"Evaluator-first bounded agent improvement: 5-dim scoring, dynamic profiling, packet-local candidates, guarded promotion.\"\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\n5: version: 1.9.0.0\n6: triggers:\n7:   - deep-agent-improvement\n8:   - agent improvement loop\n9:   - bounded agent improvement\n10:   - 5-dimension scoring\n11:   - integration scanner\n12:   - dynamic profiling\n13:   - model-benchmark mode\n14:   - benchmark a model or prompt framework\n15: ---\n16: \n17: <!-- Keywords: deep-agent-improvement, deep-agent-improvement, agent-improvement, benchmark-harness, score-candidate, promote-candidate, rollback-candidate -->\n18: \n19: # Recursive Agent: Evaluator-First Improvement Orchestrator\n20: \n21: Evaluator-first workflow for testing whether a bounded agent surface can be improved without immediately mutating the source of truth. It combines packet-local candidates, deterministic scoring, repeatable benchmarks, and explicit promotion or rollback gates.\n22: \n23: ---\n24: \n25: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n26: \n27: ### Two Co-Equal Lanes\n28: \n29: This skill supports two co-equal use-case lanes that share the same candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams:\n30: \n31: | Lane | Pick when | Command |\n32: | --- | --- | --- |\n33: | **Lane A: Agent-Improvement** | You want to improve a bounded agent `.md` file | `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` |\n34: | **Lane B: Model-Benchmark** | You want to benchmark a model or prompt framework | `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` |\n35: \n36: Lane A is detailed in §3 (Runtime Initialization, Proposal and Evaluation, Promotion and Recovery). Lane B is detailed in §4. Both lanes run the same loop shape and keep the agent-improvement path byte-identical when no mode flag is set.\n37: \n38: ### Activation Triggers\n39: \n40: Use this skill when:\n41: - You want to test whether an agent prompt or instruction surface can be improved (Lane A)\n42: - You want to benchmark a model or prompt framework against repeatable fixtures (Lane B)\n43: - The mutation boundary is explicit and narrow\n44: - You need packet-local evidence instead of ad hoc prompt tweaking\n45: - You need target-specific benchmark or scoring rules before any canonical mutation\n46: - Promotion must stay gated behind independent evidence plus operator approval\n47: \n48: ### Primary Use Cases\n49: \n50: #### Bounded Agent Improvement\n51: \n52: Use this skill to set up a proposal-first loop for any bounded agent file, write packet-local candidates, and record append-only evidence.\n53: \n54: #### Benchmark-Backed Evaluation\n55: \n56: Use this skill when candidate quality must be judged by produced artifacts and repeatability reports, not just by how a prompt file reads in isolation.\n57: \n58: #### Promotion and Rollback Verification\n59: \n60: Use this skill when you need to prove that guarded promotion, validation, rollback, and post-rollback comparison all work end to end without leaving hidden drift behind.\n61: \n62: #### Model and Prompt Benchmarking\n63: \n64: Use Lane B (model-benchmark) when the thing under test is a model or prompt framework rather than an agent definition. It runs the same loop shape against a benchmark profile and scores produced outputs, sharing the candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams with the agent-improvement path. See §4 below.\n65: \n66: ### When NOT to Use\n67: \n68: Do not use this skill for:\n69: - Open-ended prompt rewrites across multiple agent families at once\n70: - Direct canonical edits without a packet-local candidate and evaluator evidence\n71: - Broad runtime-mirror synchronization work presented as benchmark truth\n72: - General packet planning that belongs in `/speckit:plan` or implementation that does not need an improvement loop\n73: \n74: ---\n75: \n76: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n77: \n78: \n79: ### Resource Domains\n80: \n81: The router discovers markdown resources recursively from `references/` and `assets/`, then applies intent scoring so only the guidance that matches the current task is loaded.\n82: \n83: - `references/` for operator workflows, evaluator policy, promotion or rollback rules, target onboarding, and quick-reference guidance\n84: - `assets/` for reusable runtime templates such as the charter and strategy markdown files\n85: - `scripts/` for deterministic benchmark, scoring, reduction, promotion, rollback, and drift-check helpers\n86: \n87: **Lane awareness**: resources are organized by lane. `references/agent-improvement/` and `assets/agent-improvement/` carry Lane A guidance, while `references/model-benchmark/` and `assets/model-benchmark/` carry Lane B guidance. `RESOURCE_MAP` routes the `MODEL_BENCHMARK` intent to the Lane B references, and `RUNTIME_ASSETS` loads the Lane B benchmark profile only when the `MODEL_BENCHMARK` intent is selected. The `ALWAYS` and shared `references/shared/` resources apply to both lanes.\n88: \n89: ### Resource Loading Levels\n90: \n91: | Level | When to Load | Resources |\n92: | --- | --- | --- |\n93: | ALWAYS | Every skill invocation | `references/shared/quick_reference.md` |\n94: | CONDITIONAL | If intent signals match | Workflow, policy, or onboarding references |\n95: | ON_DEMAND | Only on explicit request or full setup | Markdown runtime templates in `assets/` |\n96: \n97: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n98: \n99: The authoritative routing logic for scoped markdown loading and explicit runtime-asset loading.\n100: \n101: - Pattern 1: Runtime Discovery - `discover_markdown_resources()` recursively scans `references/` and `assets/`.\n102: - Pattern 2: Existence-Check Before Load - `load_if_available()` uses `_guard_in_skill()`, `inventory`, and `seen`.\n103: - Pattern 3: Extensible Routing Key - quick-reference, loop, evaluation, promotion, target onboarding, integration, and setup intents route resources.\n104: - Pattern 4: Multi-Tier Graceful Fallback - `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST` asks for target/action/gate disambiguation and missing intent routes return a \"no knowledge base\" notice.\n105: \n106: ```python\n107: from pathlib import Path\n108: \n109: SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n110: RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\n111: DEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/shared/quick_reference.md\"\n112: \n113: INTENT_SIGNALS = {\n114:     \"QUICK_REFERENCE\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"quick reference\", \"short reminder\", \"command example\"]},\n115:     \"LOOP_EXECUTION\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"run loop\", \"proposal\", \"candidate\", \"score candidate\", \"benchmark\"]},\n116:     \"EVALUATION_POLICY\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"evaluator\", \"rubric\", \"contract\", \"repeatability\", \"no-go\"]},\n117:     \"PROMOTION_OPERATIONS\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"promote\", \"rollback\", \"mirror drift\", \"approval gate\"]},\n118:     \"TARGET_ONBOARDING\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"new target\", \"target profile\", \"onboarding\", \"second target\"]},\n119:     \"INTEGRATION_SCAN\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"integration\", \"scan surfaces\", \"mirror sync\", \"dynamic profile\", \"5-dimension\"]},\n120:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": {\"weight\": 5, \"keywords\": [\"benchmark a model\", \"benchmark a prompt framework\", \"optimize a model\", \"model-benchmark\", \"model benchmark\"]},\n121:     \"FULL_SETUP\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"full setup\", \"initialize runtime\", \"charter\", \"strategy\"]},\n122: }\n123: \n124: RESOURCE_MAP = {\n125:     \"QUICK_REFERENCE\": [\"references/shared/quick_reference.md\"],\n126:     \"LOOP_EXECUTION\": [\"references/shared/loop_protocol.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md\"],\n127:     \"EVALUATION_POLICY\": [\"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\", \"references/shared/promotion_rules.md\"],\n128:     \"PROMOTION_OPERATIONS\": [\"references/shared/rollback_runbook.md\", \"references/agent-improvement/mirror_drift_policy.md\", \"references/shared/promotion_rules.md\"],\n129:     \"TARGET_ONBOARDING\": [\"references/agent-improvement/target_onboarding.md\"],\n130:     \"INTEGRATION_SCAN\": [\"references/agent-improvement/integration_scanning.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\"],\n131:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": [\"references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\"],\n132:     \"FULL_SETUP\": [\"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_charter.md\", \"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_strategy.md\"],\n133: }\n134: \n135: RUNTIME_ASSETS = {\n136:     \"ALWAYS\": [\"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config.json\", \"assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc\"],\n137:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": [\"assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json\"],\n138: }\n139: \n140: ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS = [\"target profile\", \"score candidate\", \"proposal loop\", \"benchmark\", \"promotion gate\", \"mirror drift\"]\n141: \n142: def _task_text(task) -> str:\n143:     return \" \".join([\n144:         str(getattr(task, \"text\", \"\")),\n145:         str(getattr(task, \"query\", \"\")),\n146:         \" \".join(getattr(task, \"keywords\", []) or []),\n147:     ]).lower()\n148: \n149: UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\"Confirm target path\", \"Confirm proposal vs scoring vs promotion\", \"Confirm packet-local evidence path\"]\n150: \n151: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n152:     resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n153:     resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n154:     if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n155:         raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routed here: {relative_path}\")\n156:     return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n157: \n158: def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n159:     docs = []\n160:     for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n161:         if base.exists():\n162:             docs.extend(p for p in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if p.is_file())\n163:     return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n164: \n165: def score_intents(task) -> dict[str, float]:\n166:     text = _task_text(task)\n167:     scores = {intent: 0.0 for intent in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n168:     for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n169:         for keyword in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n170:             if keyword in text:\n171:                 scores[intent] += cfg[\"weight\"]\n172:     return scores\n173: \n174: def select_intents(scores: dict[str, float], ambiguity_delta: float = 1.0, max_intents: int = 2) -> list[str]:\n175:     ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)\n176:     if not ranked or ranked[0][1] <= 0:\n177:         return [\"QUICK_REFERENCE\"]\n178:     selected = [ranked[0][0]]\n179:     if len(ranked) > 1 and ranked[1][1] > 0 and (ranked[0][1] - ranked[1][1]) <= ambiguity_delta:\n180:         selected.append(ranked[1][0])\n181:     return selected[:max_intents]\n182: \n183: def route_recursive_agent_resources(task):\n184:     inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n185:     intents = select_intents(score_intents(task))\n186:     loaded = []\n187:     seen = set()\n188: \n189:     def load_if_available(relative_path: str) -> None:\n190:         guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n191:         if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n192:             load(guarded)\n193:             loaded.append(guarded)\n194:             seen.add(guarded)\n195: \n196:     load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n197:     for intent in intents:\n198:         for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n199:             load_if_available(relative_path)\n200: \n201:     text = _task_text(task)\n202:     if any(keyword in text for keyword in ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS):\n203:         for paths in RESOURCE_MAP.values():\n204:             for relative_path in paths:\n205:                 load_if_available(relative_path)\n206: \n207:     runtime_assets = list(RUNTIME_ASSETS[\"ALWAYS\"])\n208:     if \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\" in intents:\n209:         runtime_assets.extend(RUNTIME_ASSETS.get(\"MODEL_BENCHMARK\", []))\n210: \n211:     if not loaded:\n212:         load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n213:     return {\"intents\": intents, \"resources\": loaded, \"runtime_assets\": runtime_assets}\n214: ```\n215: \n216: ---\n217: \n218: ## 3. LANE A: AGENT-IMPROVEMENT\n219: \n220: Lane A improves a bounded agent `.md` file. Command: `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`. It runs the proposal-first loop in three modes (initialization, proposal and evaluation, promotion and recovery) and scores candidates with dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring.\n221: \n222: ### Mode 1: Runtime Initialization\n223: \n224: 1. Confirm the spec folder, target path, execution mode, and active target profile.\n225: 2. Create `{spec_folder}/improvement/` plus the packet-local `candidates/`, `benchmark-runs/`, and `archive/` directories when needed.\n226: 3. Copy in the runtime config, charter, strategy, and boundary templates.\n227: 4. Record baseline state in the append-only ledger before the first candidate run.\n228: \n229: ### Mode 2: Proposal and Evaluation\n230: \n231: 1. Read the charter, boundary file, target profile, and canonical target surface.\n232: 2. Run `scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs` to discover all surfaces the target agent touches.\n233: 3. Write exactly one bounded candidate under the packet-local `candidates/` directory.\n234: 4. Run `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs` to evaluate the candidate via dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring (the sole supported path).\n235: 5. Run `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs` to measure produced outputs against the active fixture set.\n236: 6. Append score and benchmark results to the packet-local ledger.\n237: 7. Run `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` to refresh the dashboard and experiment registry.\n238: \n239: ### Mode 2A: Stress-Test Failure Paths Before Promotion Claims\n240: \n241: For changes that alter agent discipline, run at least one same-task A/B stress scenario before recommending promotion:\n242: \n243: 1. Call A: a generic improvement attempt against an isolated sandbox copy of the target.\n244: 2. Reset the sandbox to its baseline copy.\n245: 3. Call B: the disciplined `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` path against the identical prompt and files.\n246: 4. Judge only grep/file/diff/exit-code signals: helper invocation, packet-local candidate boundary, no canonical or mirror mutation before promotion, benchmark journal boundary, legal-stop gate keys, and stop-reason correctness.\n247: \n248: Do not treat `Read(SKILL.md)` or `skill(deep-agent-improvement)` as evidence that this protocol executed.\n249: \n250: ### 5-Dimension Evaluation Framework\n251: \n252: Dynamic mode is the only scoring path. Scoring evaluates five dimensions:\n253: \n254: | Dimension | Weight | What It Measures |\n255: | --- | --- | --- |\n256: | Structural Integrity | 0.20 | Agent template compliance (required sections present) |\n257: | Rule Coherence | 0.25 | ALWAYS/NEVER rules align with workflow steps |\n258: | Integration Consistency | 0.25 | Mirrors in sync, commands reference agent, skills reference agent |\n259: | Output Quality | 0.15 | Output verification items present, no placeholder content |\n260: | System Fitness | 0.15 | Permission alignment, resource references valid, frontmatter complete |\n261: \n262: Profiles are generated on the fly from any agent file via `scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs`. No static profiles are shipped. Every target is evaluated against its own derived structure and rules.\n263: \n264: ### Mode 3: Promotion and Recovery\n265: \n266: 1. Promote only when prompt scoring, benchmark status, repeatability, boundary, and approval gates all pass.\n267: 2. Use `scripts/shared/promote-candidate.cjs` for guarded canonical mutation.\n268: 3. Use `scripts/agent-improvement/rollback-candidate.cjs` plus direct comparison evidence when the canonical target must be restored.\n269: 4. Treat mirror drift as downstream packaging work and review it separately with `scripts/agent-improvement/check-mirror-drift.cjs`.\n270: \n271: ---\n272: \n273: ## 4. LANE B: MODEL-BENCHMARK\n274: \n275: Lane B benchmarks a model or prompt framework instead of mutating an agent file. Command: `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`. Runtime entry is `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=model-benchmark`. It reuses the three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer) and keeps the default agent-improvement path byte-identical when no mode flag is set.\n276: \n277: 1. **Entry point**: `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs` resolves the mode. `--mode=agent-improvement` (or no flag) routes to `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs`. `--mode=model-benchmark` runs `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs` then `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`. An unknown mode warns and falls back to agent-improvement.\n278: 2. **Dispatcher**: `scripts/model-benchmark/dispatch-model.cjs` is the model-agnostic dispatcher (executor-routing map across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, cli-devin). It is loaded only on the model-benchmark path, never in agent-improvement mode.\n279: 3. **Scorer selection**: `run-benchmark.cjs --scorer pattern` (default) uses the heading/pattern matcher. `--scorer 5dim` routes materialized outputs through `scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/score-model-variant.cjs`, the ported 120/003 five-dimension scorer (deterministic checks plus a pluggable grader). `--grader noop` (default) stays deterministic with no model dispatch. `--grader mock` or `--grader llm` select the stub or real grader.\n280: 4. **Mode-aware records and promotion path**: every state record carries `mode: agent-improvement` or `mode: model-benchmark`, and benchmark reports carry `scoringMethod: pattern|5dim`, so the reducer (`reduce-state.cjs`) and downstream consumers can attribute results per lane. Record-level mode metadata lives in the reducer, NOT in the promoter. Lane A promotes a scored candidate through the agent-scored gates in `promote-candidate.cjs`. Lane B promotes from the benchmark report: pass `promote-candidate.cjs --benchmark-report <report.json>`, and when the report status is `benchmark-complete` with a passing benchmark recommendation, the benchmark-report path drives promotion and bypasses the agent-scored-file requirement. The promoter is NOT otherwise lane-branching beyond this benchmark-report path, both lanes share the same single canonical-target guard, archive, and runtime-mirror sync.\n281: 5. **Hardening env gates**: set `DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0` to refuse criteria-driven shell execution in the 5-dim scorer. When the gate is off, BOTH criteria-exec paths are refused: the deterministic-criterion `execSync` in `score-model-variant.cjs` AND the bundle-gate Layer-3 acceptance-command `execSync` in `bundle-gate.cjs`. Set `DEEP_AGENT_GRADER_CACHE_RAW=0` to redact raw grader output from the on-disk cache. Both default to the permissive value for backward-compat. **Trusted-author default rationale (DOCUMENT-ACCEPT)**: criteria commands originate only from benchmark profiles authored by the operator running the loop, and the deterministic criterion runs in the same trust domain as the loop itself, so the default-on behavior is an intended trusted-author boundary rather than an untrusted-input risk. A shipped backward-compat test asserts the criterion runs by default, so flipping the default would be a behavior change with test impact, not a silent hardening. Hardened or shared-runner deployments set `DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0` to fail closed, and `DEEP_AGENT_GRADER_CACHE_RAW=0` to redact cached grader output.\n282: \n283: ---\n284: \n285: ## 5. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n286: \n287: - The loop stays proposal-first unless an explicit guarded promotion path is requested\n288: - Benchmark evidence, prompt scoring, and mirror-sync evidence remain separate\n289: - Reducer outputs make the best-known state, rejected runs, infrastructure failures, and stop conditions easy to review\n290: - Operators can onboard a bounded target without weakening boundary or evaluator guardrails\n291: \n292: ---\n293: \n294: ## 6. MULTI-ITER METHODOLOGY\n295: \n296: For multi-iter evaluation sweeps, a mixed-executor split plus an adjudication pass gives better breadth, better synthesis, and less noise than a single-executor run.\n297: \n298: - **Mixed-executor 8+2 split**: run breadth iterations on cli-devin SWE-1.6 and synthesis iterations on cli-codex gpt-5.5. For a 10-iter sweep, that is iters 1-8 breadth and iters 9-10 synthesis.\n299: - **Adjudication iter**: insert a false-positive filter pass before the synthesis iterations (typically the iter-7 mark) so only confirmed findings carry forward. In validation this delivers a 90%+ false-positive reduction, with one pass dropping 9 false-positive and 4 outdated items to take a 20-item queue down to 7.\n300: \n301: See `references/model-benchmark/mixed_executor_methodology.md` for the split mechanics, adjudication details, and the full validation evidence.\n302: \n303: ---\n304: \n305: ## 7. RUNTIME TRUTH CONTRACTS\n306: \n307: ### Stop-Reason Taxonomy\n308: \n309: Every improvement session termination MUST produce both a `stopReason` (why) and a `sessionOutcome` (what happened).\n310: \n311: **stopReason** (WHY the session ended):\n312: \n313: | Reason | Trigger Condition |\n314: | --- | --- |\n315: | `converged` | All legal-stop gate bundles pass and dimension trajectory is stable |\n316: | `maxIterationsReached` | Iteration counter equals `maxIterations` config |\n317: | `blockedStop` | One or more legal-stop gate bundles fail when convergence math would otherwise trigger stop |\n318: | `manualStop` | Operator cancels the session |\n319: | `error` | Infra failure, script crash, or unrecoverable condition |\n320: | `stuckRecovery` | Session detected stuck state and exhausted recovery options |\n321: \n322: **sessionOutcome** (WHAT happened to the candidate):\n323: \n324: | Outcome | When Used |\n325: | --- | --- |\n326: | `keptBaseline` | Baseline was retained because candidate did not improve |\n327: | `promoted` | Candidate was promoted to canonical target |\n328: | `rolledBack` | Promoted candidate was rolled back to prior state |\n329: | `advisoryOnly` | Session completed for assessment only; no mutation attempted |\n330: \n331: ### Audit Journal Protocol\n332: \n333: All journal emission is orchestrator-only (ADR-001). The journal (`improvement-journal.jsonl`) is an append-only JSONL file capturing lifecycle events. Separate from the existing `agent-improvement-state.jsonl` which tracks proposal/evaluation data.\n334: \n335: **Script**: `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`\n336: \n337: Event types: `session_start`, `session_initialized`, `integration_scanned`, `candidate_generated`, `candidate_scored`, `benchmark_completed`, `gate_evaluation`, `legal_stop_evaluated`, `blocked_stop`, `promotion_attempt`, `promotion_result`, `rollback`, `rollback_result`, `trade_off_detected`, `mutation_proposed`, `mutation_outcome`, `session_ended`, `session_end`\n338: \n339: ### Static Benchmark Assets\n340: \n341: The reusable benchmark contract ships with the skill, not with each spec packet:\n342: \n343: - Profile: `assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json`\n344: - Fixtures: `assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-fixtures/*.json`\n345: - Materializer: `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs`\n346: - Runner: `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`\n347: \n348: The command workflow first materializes static fixture JSON into packet-local markdown under `{spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs/{fixture.id}.md`, then runs `run-benchmark.cjs --profile .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json --outputs-dir {spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs`. The runner writes `{spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs/report.json` with `status:\"benchmark-complete\"` and appends a `benchmark_run` row to `{spec_folder}/improvement/agent-improvement-state.jsonl`.\n349: \n350: `benchmark_completed` may be emitted only after `benchmark-outputs/report.json` exists. Repeatability output from `benchmark-stability.cjs` is separate evidence and does not by itself prove benchmark completion.\n351: \n352: ### Legal-Stop Gate Bundles\n353: \n354: A session may NOT claim `converged` unless all five gate bundles pass: `contractGate`, `behaviorGate`, `integrationGate`, `evidenceGate`, and `improvementGate`. The orchestrator emits `legal_stop_evaluated` with nested `details.gateResults` before any `session_end`. Failures emit `blocked_stop` with `failedGates[]` and `stopReason:\"blockedStop\"`.\n355: \n356: ### Resume/Continuation Semantics (current release)\n357: \n358: Sessions support a single lineage mode today: `new`. Every invocation of the `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` workflow starts a fresh session with a new session id and generation 1. Multi-generation lineage modes (`resume`, `restart`, `fork`, `completed-continue`) were described in earlier drafts but have no shipped runtime wiring in the deep-agent-improvement workflow, reducer, or journal consumer.\n359: \n360: Operators who want to continue evaluating an agent after a prior session SHOULD archive the prior session folder (e.g. move `improve/` to `improve_archive/{timestamp}/`) and re-invoke the command, which starts a new `new`-mode session. The reducer treats each session independently and does not carry ancestry across sessions.\n361: \n362: If the long-form lineage feature is implemented later, it will arrive with first-class event emission in `deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_{auto,confirm}.yaml`, reducer ancestry handling in `deep-agent-improvement/scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs`, and replay fixtures. Until then, treat every session as a standalone evaluation.\n363: \n364: ### Mutation Coverage Graph\n365: \n366: **Script**: `scripts/shared/mutation-coverage.cjs`\n367: \n368: Tracks explored dimensions, tried mutation types per dimension, and exhausted mutation sets using `loop_type: \"improvement\"` namespace isolation (ADR-002). The orchestrator skips mutation types already in the exhausted log.\n369: \n370: #### Mutation Signature Dedup\n371: \n372: Each mutation entry in `mutation-coverage.json` carries a `signature` field computed as:\n373: \n374: ```text\n375: signature = sha256(dimension + \"\\u001f\" + mutationType + \"\\u001f\" + targetSection + \"\\u001f\" + normalizedBody64)\n376: ```\n377: \n378: Where `normalizedBody64` = whitespace-collapsed, lowercased, first 64 characters of the mutation body.\n379: \n380: **Dedup behavior:**\n381: - Before proposing a new mutation, `isSignatureSeen()` scans existing `mutations[]` and `exhausted[]` arrays\n382: - If the signature matches, the candidate is skipped with `reason: \"EXHAUSTED-FROM: iter-NNN\"` recorded in `exhausted[]`\n383: - The `EXHAUSTED-FROM` format references the iteration where the original mutation was tried\n384: \n385: **Bypass:**\n386: ```bash\n387: export DEEP_AGENT_IMPROVEMENT_SKIP_DEDUP=1  # Force re-evaluation of previously seen signatures\n388: ```\n389: When set, `isSignatureSeen()` always returns `{ seen: false }`. Every mutation is considered fresh.\n390: \n391: **Backward compatibility:** Legacy `mutation-coverage.json` entries without `signature` field fall back to the existing `dimension::mutationType` dedup in the reducer. No migration required.\n392: \n393: **Authoritative storage:** `mutation-coverage.json` `mutations[]` array. `signature` is written by `recordMutation()` and read by `isSignatureSeen()` and `reduce-state.cjs`.\n394: \n395: ### Dimension Trajectory\n396: \n397: Trajectory data records per-iteration dimension scores. Two distinct convergence signals run side by side and must not be conflated. `mutation-coverage.cjs` `checkConvergenceEligibility()` marks a profile convergence-eligible when it has at least 3 data points and every dimension delta across the last 3 points is within `DEFAULT_STABILITY_DELTA` (+/-2), a tolerance band. Separately, `reduce-state.cjs` `stopOnDimensionPlateau` fires the plateau stop only when a dimension's last 3 scores are identical (exact-repeat). The +/-2 trajectory eligibility and the exact-repeat plateau stop are different checks.\n398: \n399: Stop-condition counters (`maxConsecutiveTies`, `maxInfraFailuresPerProfile`, `maxWeakBenchmarkRunsPerProfile`) default to disabled, with no cap, unless the runtime config sets them. Only configured counters can trigger `blockedStop`.\n400: \n401: ### Trade-Off Detection\n402: \n403: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/trade-off-detector.cjs`\n404: \n405: Detects Pareto trade-offs: flags when improvement > +3 in one dimension causes regression < -3 in hard dimensions (structural, integration, systemFitness) or < -5 in soft dimensions (ruleCoherence, outputQuality). Blocks promotion for Pareto-dominated candidates.\n406: \n407: ### Parallel Candidate Waves (Optional)\n408: \n409: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/candidate-lineage.cjs`\n410: \n411: Disabled by default (`parallelWaves.enabled: false` in config, ADR-004). When enabled, spawns 2-3 candidates with different mutation strategies. Activation requires: exploration-breadth score above threshold, 3+ unresolved mutation families, and 2 consecutive tie/plateau iterations.\n412: \n413: ### Weight Optimizer (Advisory Only)\n414: \n415: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/benchmark-stability.cjs`\n416: \n417: Reads historical session data and emits a weight-recommendation report. Recommendations do NOT auto-apply (ADR-005). Requires minimum session count threshold before producing recommendations.\n418: \n419: ---\n420: \n421: ### Journal Wiring Contract\n422: \n423: Journal emission is orchestrator-only. The target agent being evaluated never writes journal rows directly. Only the visible YAML workflow or an operator-side wrapper invokes `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`.\n424: \n425: The CLI contract is:\n426: \n427: ```bash\n428: node .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs --emit <eventType> --journal <journal_path> --details '<json>'\n429: ```\n430: \n431: The helper validates event type plus `session_end` or `session_ended` details, and the CLI entrypoint stores boundary context under `details`. Top-level `iteration` and `candidateId` fields are available only through the JS API, not through the CLI wrapper used by the YAML workflows.\n432: \n433: ### Boundary Points\n434: \n435: Journal boundaries are `session_start` after baseline setup, per-iteration candidate/scoring/gate events, and `session_end` after synthesis or terminal stop. Required details include session id, target, iteration/candidate paths, scores, stop reason, session outcome, and total iterations.\n436: \n437: ### Frozen Helper Enums\n438: \n439: `improvement-journal.cjs` currently exports and validates the following enums:\n440: \n441: - `STOP_REASONS`: `converged`, `maxIterationsReached`, `blockedStop`, `manualStop`, `error`, `stuckRecovery`\n442: - `SESSION_OUTCOMES`: `keptBaseline`, `promoted`, `rolledBack`, `advisoryOnly`\n443: \n444: Keep session-end emissions aligned to those helper-owned values until the helper contract itself changes. Labels such as `convergedImprovement`, `plateau`, `benchmarkPlateau`, `rejected`, `deferred`, `blocked`, or `errored` are not accepted by the current CLI validator. Plateau detection is a reducer/stop-rule condition. It must reconcile to one of the canonical stop reasons above when emitted as `details.stopReason`.\n445: \n446: ### Orchestrator Ownership\n447: \n448: - Auto mode emits `session_start` after `step_record_baseline`, then emits `candidate_generated`, `candidate_scored`, and `gate_evaluation` inside each loop iteration, and finally emits `session_end` after synthesis.\n449: - Confirm mode mirrors the same boundaries, with `gate_evaluation` emitted after the operator-facing approval gate is resolved.\n450: - Operators invoking the helper manually must use the same boundary order so replay and reducer consumers see a consistent journal shape.\n451: \n452: ### Reducer Consumer Side\n453: \n454: The reducer is the consumer for replay artifacts on refresh. Every `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` pass now attempts to read:\n455: \n456: - `improvement-journal.jsonl`\n457: - `candidate-lineage.json`\n458: - `mutation-coverage.json`\n459: \n460: These inputs remain optional. Missing files do not fail the reducer. The corresponding registry field is set to `null` so dashboard and registry refreshes still complete.\n461: \n462: For legal-stop replay, the reducer consumes `details.gateResults` from the latest `legal_stop_evaluated` event and surfaces it as `journalSummary.latestLegalStop.gateResults` in `experiment-registry.json` plus the dashboard's latest legal-stop table.\n463: \n464: ### Journal Replay Consumer\n465: \n466: The reducer consumes replay artifacts instead of running a separate orchestrator-only synthesis step. During each refresh pass, `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` reads the following artifacts when present:\n467: \n468: - `improvement-journal.jsonl` to summarize last session boundaries, total replayed events, per-event counts, and terminal `stopReason` / `sessionOutcome`\n469: - `candidate-lineage.json` to summarize lineage depth, total candidate count, and the latest candidate leaf\n470: - `mutation-coverage.json` to summarize mutation coverage ratio and uncovered mutations\n471: \n472: The reducer writes these summaries into new top-level registry fields:\n473: \n474: - `journalSummary`\n475: - `candidateLineage`\n476: - `mutationCoverage`\n477: \n478: Graceful degradation is required: if any artifact is missing, unreadable, or not yet generated for the current runtime, the reducer preserves the rest of the registry and records `null` for that field instead of throwing.\n479: \n480: The dashboard now also includes a dedicated **Sample Quality** section. This separates replay/stability sample sufficiency from benchmark failures so operators can tell the difference between a true regression and an iteration that simply lacked enough data for trade-off or replay-stability trust.\n481: \n482: ## 8. RULES\n483: \n484: ### ✅ ALWAYS\n485: \n486: - Read the charter, boundary file, and target profile before creating a candidate\n487: - Keep the ledger append-only\n488: - Treat the scorer as independent from the mutator\n489: - Preserve repeatability evidence when benchmark claims are made\n490: - Prefer the simpler candidate when scores tie\n491: - Keep benchmark evidence separate from mirror-drift packaging work\n492: - Require integration evidence to name each expected runtime mirror path explicitly (`.claude/agents`, `.codex/agents`, `.gemini/agents`, plus any declared extra mirrors) before trusting `integrationGate`\n493: \n494: ### ❌ NEVER\n495: \n496: - Mutate the canonical target during proposal-only mode\n497: - Broaden scope beyond the active boundary\n498: - Treat runtime mirrors as experiment truth in the same phase as canonical evaluation\n499: - Treat a stale placeholder mirror path as equivalent to a real runtime mirror\n500: - Hide rejected runs, weak benchmark results, or infra failures\n501: - Promote non-canonical targets even if they benchmark well\n502: \n503: ### ⚠️ ESCALATE IF\n504: \n505: - The target profile and boundary file disagree about mutability or target family\n506: - The benchmark runner cannot produce stable repeatability results\n507: - Promotion evidence is incomplete but canonical mutation is still being requested\n508: - Documentation edits would change the trust boundary rather than clarify it\n509: \n510: ---\n511: \n512: ## 9. REFERENCES\n513: \n514: Core references: `README.md`, `references/shared/quick_reference.md`, `references/shared/loop_protocol.md`, evaluator/promotion/rollback/no-go/onboarding docs, runtime assets under `assets/`, benchmark assets, and helper scripts for scoring, reduction, promotion, rollback, scanning, drift, journal, mutation coverage, trade-offs, candidate lineage, and benchmark stability.\n515: \n516: ---\n517: \n518: ## 10. INTEGRATION POINTS\n519: \n520: - `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` initializes and runs the Lane A bounded workflow\n521: - `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` initializes and runs the Lane B model-benchmark workflow\n522: - `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` provides the mutator surface for deep-agent-improvement runs\n523: - `sk-doc` validators enforce package-shape, README, and markdown document consistency\n524: - `system-spec-kit` packet validation proves phase records remain truthful\n525: \n526: ---\n527: \n528: ## 11. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n529: \n530: The router discovers reference, asset, and script docs dynamically. Start with `references/shared/loop_protocol.md`, `references/shared/quick_reference.md`, `references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md`, `references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md`, `references/agent-improvement/integration_scanning.md`, `references/agent-improvement/mirror_drift_policy.md`, `references/shared/promotion_rules.md`, then load task-specific resources from `references/`, templates from `assets/`, and automation from `scripts/` when present.\n531: \n532: Scripts: `scripts/agent-improvement/benchmark-stability.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/candidate-lineage.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/check-mirror-drift.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs`, `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`, `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs`, `scripts/shared/mutation-coverage.cjs`, `scripts/shared/promote-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/rollback-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/trade-off-detector.cjs`.\n533: \n534: Related skills: `sk-doc` for package-shape and markdown validation, `system-spec-kit` for packet validation, and `sk-prompt` when prompt surfaces need evaluator-backed rewriting.\n\n(End of file - total 534 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: deep-agent-improvement\ndescription: \"Evaluator-first bounded agent improvement: 5-dim scoring, dynamic profiling, packet-local candidates, guarded promotion.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\nversion: 1.9.0.0\ntriggers:\n  - deep-agent-improvement\n  - agent improvement loop\n  - bounded agent improvement\n  - 5-dimension scoring\n  - integration scanner\n  - dynamic profiling\n  - model-benchmark mode\n  - benchmark a model or prompt framework\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: deep-agent-improvement, deep-agent-improvement, agent-improvement, benchmark-harness, score-candidate, promote-candidate, rollback-candidate -->\n\n# Recursive Agent: Evaluator-First Improvement Orchestrator\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1780129625892,"end":1780129625907}},"id":"prt_e77fe7543001A7m2drQxvCE42B","sessionID":"ses_18801b231ffe1T23Rry15kpUZw","messageID":"msg_e77fe4fd1001FDfxxzWTB1lAMJ"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129626510,"sessionID":"ses_18801b231ffe1T23Rry15kpUZw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_01_Cb1SBORF7f3Wx1HoX4RW9850","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: sk-doc\n3: description: \"Markdown and OpenCode component specialist: doc quality, content optimization, component scaffolds, install guides, playbooks.\"\n4: allowed-tools: [Bash, Edit, Glob, Grep, Read, Task, Write]\n5: version: 1.5.0.0\n6: ---\n7: \n8: <!-- Keywords: sk-doc, markdown-quality, skill-creation, document-validation, ascii-flowchart, llms-txt, content-optimization, extract-structure -->\n9: \n10: # Documentation Creation Specialist - Unified Markdown & Component Management\n11: \n12: Unified specialist providing: (1) Document quality pipeline with structure enforcement and content optimization, (2) OpenCode component creation (skills, agents, commands) with scaffolding, validation and packaging, (3) ASCII flowchart creation for visualizing workflows, (4) Install guide creation for setup documentation and (5) Feature catalog and manual testing playbook creation for inventory and validation packages.\n13: \n14: **Core Principle**: Structure first, then content, then quality.\n15: \n16: **Architecture**: Scripts handle deterministic parsing/metrics. AI handles quality judgment and recommendations.\n17: \n18: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n19: \n20: ### Use Case: Document Quality Management\n21: \n22: Enforce markdown structure, optimize content for AI assistants, validate quality through script-assisted AI analysis.\n23: \n24: **README Creation** - Use `readme_template.md` + `readme_creation.md` when:\n25: - Creating new README for any folder or project\n26: - User requests \"create a README\", \"add documentation\", \"write a README\"\n27: - Folder needs comprehensive documentation\n28: - Workflow: [readme_creation.md](./references/readme_creation.md) | Template: [readme_template.md](./assets/readme/readme_template.md)\n29: \n30: **Skill README Creation** - Use `skill_readme_template.md` when:\n31: - Creating or refreshing `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/README.md`\n32: - A skill README needs human-facing purpose, quick start, structure, examples, troubleshooting, FAQ or related-resource navigation\n33: - Template: [skill_readme_template.md](./assets/skill/skill_readme_template.md)\n34: \n35: **Frontmatter Validation** - Use `frontmatter_templates.md` when:\n36: - Validating YAML frontmatter in any document\n37: - Checking required fields for document types\n38: - Fixing frontmatter syntax errors\n39: \n40: **Changelog & Release Notes** - Use `changelog_template.md` when:\n41: - Authoring a global component changelog at `.opencode/changelog/{NN--component}/v{VERSION}.md`\n42: - Composing GitHub release notes that mirror the changelog body\n43: - Choosing between compact (under 10 changes) and expanded (10+ changes or major) formats\n44: - Template: [changelog_template.md](./assets/changelog_template.md). Used by `/create:changelog` (auto + confirm). Nested packet-local changelogs use the spec-kit templates at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/templates/changelog/` instead.\n45: \n46: **Validation Workflow** - Apply after Write/Edit operations:\n47: - Auto-correct filename violations (ALL CAPS to lowercase, hyphens to underscores)\n48: - Fix safe violations (separators, H2 case)\n49: - Check critical violations (missing frontmatter, wrong section order)\n50: \n51: **Manual Optimization** - Run when:\n52: - README needs optimization for AI assistants\n53: - Creating critical documentation (specs, knowledge, skills)\n54: - Pre-release quality checks\n55: - Generating llms.txt for LLM navigation\n56: \n57: ### Use Case: OpenCode Component Creation\n58: \n59: Create and manage OpenCode components (skills, agents, commands). Each component type has templates and validation with quality standards.\n60: \n61: **Component Types:**\n62: - **Skills** (.opencode/skills/) - Knowledge bundles with workflows → [skill_creation.md](./references/skill_creation.md)\n63: - **Agents** (.opencode/agents/) - AI personas with tool permissions → [agent_creation.md](./references/agent_creation.md)\n64: - **Commands** (.opencode/commands/) - Slash commands for user invocation → [command_template.md](./assets/command_template.md)\n65: \n66: For larger skills, split deep content into focused reference files and keep concise navigation in `SKILL.md` or `README.md`. When a skill has both cross-cutting standards and document-family guides, prefer `references/global/` for shared rules and the `references/` root for creation-specific workflows.\n67: \n68: Start with: [skill_creation.md](./references/skill_creation.md) (Section 9)\n69: Primary templates:\n70: - [skill_md_template.md](./assets/skill/skill_md_template.md)\n71: - [skill_readme_template.md](./assets/skill/skill_readme_template.md)\n72: - [skill_reference_template.md](./assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md)\n73: - [skill_asset_template.md](./assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md)\n74: \n75: **Use when**:\n76: - User requests skill creation (\"create a skill\", \"make a new skill\")\n77: - User requests agent creation (\"create an agent\", \"make a new agent\")\n78: - User requests command creation (\"create a command\", \"add a slash command\")\n79: - Scaffolding component structure\n80: - Validating component quality\n81: - Packaging skill for distribution\n82: \n83: **Skill Process (6 steps)**: Understanding (examples) → Planning (resources) → Initialization (`init_skill.py`) → Editing (populate) → Packaging (`package_skill.py`) → Iteration (test/improve)\n84: \n85: **Agent Process**: Load `agent_creation.md` and `agent_template.md` → Define frontmatter (mode, permissions) → Create sections (workflow, capabilities, anti-patterns) → Validate → Test\n86: \n87: **Command Process**: Load `command_template.md` → Define frontmatter (name, description) → Create execution logic → Add to command registry → Test\n88: \n89: ### Use Case: Flowchart Creation\n90: \n91: Create ASCII flowcharts for visualizing workflows, user journeys and decision trees.\n92: \n93: For styled HTML visuals (interactive diagrams, dashboard pages, or polished data-table renders), use a dedicated HTML workflow instead of forcing ASCII or markdown flowcharts.\n94: \n95: **Use when**:\n96: - Documenting multi-step processes with branching\n97: - Creating decision trees with multiple outcomes\n98: - Showing parallel execution with sync points\n99: - Visualizing approval gates and revision cycles\n100: \n101: **See**: [assets/flowcharts/](./assets/flowcharts/)\n102: \n103: ### Use Case: Install Guide Creation\n104: \n105: Create and validate installation documentation for MCP servers, plugins and tools using phase-based templates.\n106: \n107: **Use when**:\n108: - Creating documentation for MCP server installation\n109: - Documenting plugin setup procedures\n110: - Standardizing tool installation across platforms\n111: - Need phase-based validation checkpoints\n112: \n113: **5-Phase Process**: Overview → Prerequisites → Installation → Configuration → Verification\n114: \n115: **See**: [install_guide_creation.md](./references/install_guide_creation.md)\n116: \n117: ### Use Case: Manual Testing Playbook Creation\n118: \n119: Create manual testing playbooks with deterministic scenarios, structured evidence collection, and multi-agent execution planning.\n120: \n121: **Manual Testing Playbook** - Use `testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook_template.md` when:\n122: - Creating manual testing scenarios for a skill\n123: - Standardizing test evidence and verdict criteria\n124: - Setting up multi-agent test execution planning\n125: \n126: **Canonical Package**: Root `manual_testing_playbook.md` plus numbered category folders with one per-feature file per feature ID.\n127: \n128: **See**:\n129: - [manual_testing_playbook_creation.md](./references/manual_testing_playbook_creation.md)\n130: - [manual_testing_playbook_template.md](./assets/testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook_template.md)\n131: \n132: ### Use Case: Feature Catalog Creation\n133: \n134: Create feature catalogs with a rooted feature inventory, numbered category sections, and per-feature reference files.\n135: \n136: **Feature Catalog** - Use `assets/feature_catalog/feature_catalog_template.md` when:\n137: - Creating a canonical current-state feature inventory for a skill or system\n138: - Linking manual playbooks back to a stable feature reference\n139: - Documenting current behavior with source-file anchors and stable slugs\n140: \n141: **Canonical Package**: Root `FEATURE_CATALOG.md` plus numbered category folders with one per-feature file per catalog entry.\n142: \n143: **See**:\n144: - [feature_catalog_creation.md](./references/feature_catalog_creation.md)\n145: - [feature_catalog_template.md](./assets/feature_catalog/feature_catalog_template.md)\n146: \n147: ### Use Case: Benchmark Folder Creation\n148: \n149: Create skill-local `mcp_server/benchmarks/benchmark-<YYYY-MM-DD>/` folders that promote curated bake-off results from an originating spec packet into the consuming skill, where operators reading the MCP code can find the headline without leaving the skill tree.\n150: \n151: **Benchmark Creation** - Use `benchmark_report_template.md` plus `source_template.md` when:\n152: - An ADR or spec packet has just promoted a non-trivial default change (embedder swap, reranker change, retrieval policy) backed by measured evidence\n153: - The originating spec packet has a stable headline plus replay commands and is worth surfacing inside the consuming skill\n154: - A sibling skill already ships a `mcp_server/benchmarks/` folder and parity matters for operators moving between skills\n155: \n156: **Canonical Package**: One `benchmark-<YYYY-MM-DD>/` folder per run, holding `benchmark_report.md` (ten-section curated narrative), `SOURCE.md` (wayfinding pointer back to the spec packet), `results.csv`, `*.jsonl` per-probe data, and optional sidecars (`runtime-measurements.md`, `risk-analysis-*.md`).\n157: \n158: **See**:\n159: - [benchmark_creation.md](./references/benchmark_creation.md)\n160: - [benchmark_report_template.md](./assets/benchmark/benchmark_report_template.md)\n161: - [source_template.md](./assets/benchmark/source_template.md)\n162: \n163: ### When NOT to Use (All Modes)\n164: \n165: - Non-markdown files (only `.md` supported)\n166: - Simple typo fixes (use Edit tool directly)\n167: - Internal notes or drafts\n168: - Auto-generated API docs\n169: - Short 2-3 step processes (use bullet points)\n170: \n171: ---\n172: \n173: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n174: \n175: > Pattern: see [sk-doc smart-router resilience template](./assets/skill/skill_smart_router.md).\n176: \n177: ### Resource Domains\n178: \n179: The router discovers markdown resources recursively from `references/` and `assets/` and then applies intent scoring from `RESOURCE_MAP`. Keep this section domain-focused rather than static file inventories.\n180: \n181: - `references/global/` for documentation standards, validation rules, optimization guidance, voice rules, and shared execution workflows.\n182: - `references/` root for document-family and component creation guides such as skill creation, agent creation, install guides, feature catalogs, and manual testing playbooks.\n183: - `assets/readme/` for README and install-guide scaffolds; `assets/changelog_template.md`, `assets/frontmatter_templates.md`, and `assets/llmstxt_templates.md` at the assets/ root for cross-cutting templates.\n184: - `assets/skill/` for skill creation templates, including `SKILL.md`, skill README, reference and asset scaffolds; `assets/agent_template.md` and `assets/command_template.md` at the assets/ root for agent and command creation templates.\n185: - `assets/feature_catalog/` and `assets/testing_playbook/` at the assets/ root for feature catalog and manual testing playbook package templates.\n186: - `assets/benchmark/` for skill-local benchmark folder templates (`benchmark_report_template.md`, `source_template.md`).\n187: - `assets/flowcharts/` for reusable ASCII flowchart patterns and diagram examples.\n188: \n189: > **Cross-CLI consumption note** (per packets 071/072 stress-test data): when sk-doc is dispatched via an external CLI and the caller consumes the routing-trace output LITERALLY (e.g. attempts to `Read()` cited resource paths), prefer **cli-codex** (gpt-5.5/high/fast) — it scored 66.7% resource-accuracy vs cli-opencode 47.2% on the sk-doc router stress matrix. claude-opus-4.7 tends to hallucinate plausible-sounding paths that don't exist in this skill's filesystem; treat its routing trace as advisory and verify cited paths before reading. See the local router stress-test notes for the full data and hallucination finding.\n190: \n191: ### Resource Loading Levels\n192: \n193: | Level       | When to Load             | Resources                   |\n194: | ----------- | ------------------------ | --------------------------- |\n195: | ALWAYS      | Every skill invocation   | Quick reference baseline    |\n196: | CONDITIONAL | If intent signals match  | Mode-specific docs/templates|\n197: | ON_DEMAND   | Only on explicit request | Extended standards/template |\n198: \n199: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n200: \n201: The authoritative routing logic for scoped loading, weighted intent scoring, and ambiguity handling.\n202: \n203: - Pattern 1: Runtime Discovery - `discover_markdown_resources()` recursively scans `references/` and `assets/`.\n204: - Pattern 2: Existence-Check Before Load - `load_if_available()` guards, checks `inventory`, and suppresses repeats with `seen`.\n205: - Pattern 3: Extensible Routing Key - intent labels route to document families without static inventories.\n206: - Pattern 4: Multi-Tier Graceful Fallback - `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` requests disambiguation and missing families return a \"no knowledge base\" notice.\n207: \n208: ```python\n209: from pathlib import Path\n210: \n211: SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n212: RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\n213: DEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/global/quick_reference.md\"\n214: \n215: INTENT_SIGNALS = {\n216:     \"DOC_QUALITY\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"dqi\", \"quality\", \"validate\", \"extract_structure\"]},\n217:     \"OPTIMIZATION\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"optimize\", \"llms.txt\", \"ai context\"]},\n218:     \"SKILL_CREATION\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"skill creation\", \"new skill\", \"init_skill\", \"package_skill\"]},\n219:     \"AGENT_COMMAND\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"create agent\", \"create command\", \"agent template\", \"command template\"]},\n220:     \"FLOWCHART\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"flowchart\", \"ascii diagram\", \"decision tree\", \"swimlane\"]},\n221:     \"INSTALL_GUIDE\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"install guide\", \"setup instructions\", \"prerequisite\"]},\n222:     \"HVR\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"human voice\", \"hvr\", \"voice rules\", \"banned words\", \"writing style\"]},\n223:     \"PLAYBOOK\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"playbook\", \"manual testing\", \"test scenarios\", \"manual test\", \"testing playbook\"]},\n224:     \"FEATURE_CATALOG\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"feature catalog\", \"feature inventory\", \"catalog snippet\"]},\n225:     \"README_CREATION\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"create readme\", \"readme creation\", \"write readme\", \"add documentation\", \"folder readme\"]},\n226:     \"CHANGELOG\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"changelog\", \"release notes\", \"changelog template\", \"release template\", \"create changelog\", \"github release\"]},\n227:     \"BENCHMARK\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"benchmark\", \"benchmark creation\", \"benchmark report\", \"mcp_server benchmarks\", \"benchmark_report.md\", \"skill-local benchmark\", \"benchmark folder\", \"source.md template\"]},\n228: }\n229: \n230: RESOURCE_MAP = {\n231:     \"DOC_QUALITY\": [\"references/global/validation.md\", \"references/global/workflows.md\", \"references/global/core_standards.md\", \"references/global/evergreen_packet_id_rule.md\"],\n232:     \"OPTIMIZATION\": [\"references/global/optimization.md\", \"assets/llmstxt_templates.md\"],\n233:     \"SKILL_CREATION\": [\"references/skill_creation.md\", \"assets/skill/skill_md_template.md\", \"assets/skill/skill_readme_template.md\", \"assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md\"],\n234:     \"AGENT_COMMAND\": [\"references/agent_creation.md\", \"assets/agent_template.md\", \"assets/command_template.md\"],\n235:     \"FLOWCHART\": [\"assets/flowcharts/simple_workflow.md\", \"assets/flowcharts/decision_tree_flow.md\"],\n236:     \"INSTALL_GUIDE\": [\"assets/readme/install_guide_template.md\", \"references/install_guide_creation.md\"],\n237:     \"HVR\": [\"references/global/hvr_rules.md\"],\n238:     \"PLAYBOOK\": [\"references/manual_testing_playbook_creation.md\", \"assets/testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook_template.md\"],\n239:     \"FEATURE_CATALOG\": [\"references/feature_catalog_creation.md\", \"assets/feature_catalog/feature_catalog_template.md\"],\n240:     \"README_CREATION\": [\"references/readme_creation.md\", \"assets/readme/readme_template.md\"],\n241:     \"CHANGELOG\": [\"assets/changelog_template.md\"],\n242:     \"BENCHMARK\": [\"references/benchmark_creation.md\", \"assets/benchmark/benchmark_report_template.md\", \"assets/benchmark/source_template.md\"],\n243: }\n244: \n245: LOADING_LEVELS = {\n246:     \"ALWAYS\": [DEFAULT_RESOURCE],\n247:     \"ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS\": [\"full standards\", \"all templates\", \"deep dive\", \"readme\", \"documentation\", \"manual testing playbook\", \"feature catalog\", \"release notes\", \"corpus/readme\", \"corpus documentation\"],\n248:     \"ON_DEMAND\": [\"assets/frontmatter_templates.md\"],\n249: }\n250: \n251: UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\n252:     \"Confirm whether this is document quality, component creation, flowchart, install guide, playbook, or catalog work\",\n253:     \"Confirm the expected output file or component type\",\n254:     \"Provide one example input or target document\",\n255:     \"Confirm whether full templates or a quick reference are needed\",\n256: ]\n257: \n258: def _task_text(task) -> str:\n259:     return \" \".join([\n260:         str(getattr(task, \"text\", \"\")),\n261:         str(getattr(task, \"query\", \"\")),\n262:         \" \".join(getattr(task, \"keywords\", []) or []),\n263:     ]).lower()\n264: \n265: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n266:     resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n267:     resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n268:     if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n269:         raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routable: {relative_path}\")\n270:     return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n271: \n272: def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n273:     docs = []\n274:     for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n275:         if base.exists():\n276:             docs.extend(p for p in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if p.is_file())\n277:     return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n278: \n279: def score_intents(task) -> dict[str, float]:\n280:     \"\"\"Weighted intent scoring from request text and documentation modes.\"\"\"\n281:     text = _task_text(task)\n282:     scores = {intent: 0.0 for intent in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n283:     for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n284:         for keyword in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n285:             if keyword in text:\n286:                 scores[intent] += cfg[\"weight\"]\n287:     return scores\n288: \n289: def select_intents(scores: dict[str, float], ambiguity_delta: float = 1.0, max_intents: int = 2) -> list[str]:\n290:     ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)\n291:     if not ranked or ranked[0][1] <= 0:\n292:         return [\"DOC_QUALITY\"]\n293:     selected = [ranked[0][0]]\n294:     if len(ranked) > 1 and ranked[1][1] > 0 and (ranked[0][1] - ranked[1][1]) <= ambiguity_delta:\n295:         selected.append(ranked[1][0])\n296:     return selected[:max_intents]\n297: \n298: def route_documentation_resources(task):\n299:     inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n300:     scores = score_intents(task)\n301:     intents = select_intents(scores, ambiguity_delta=1.0)\n302:     loaded = []\n303:     seen = set()\n304: \n305:     def load_if_available(relative_path: str) -> None:\n306:         guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n307:         if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n308:             load(guarded)\n309:             loaded.append(guarded)\n310:             seen.add(guarded)\n311: \n312:     for relative_path in LOADING_LEVELS[\"ALWAYS\"]:\n313:         load_if_available(relative_path)\n314: \n315:     if max(scores.values() or [0]) < 0.5:\n316:         return {\n317:             \"intents\": intents,\n318:             \"intent_scores\": scores,\n319:             \"load_level\": \"UNKNOWN_FALLBACK\",\n320:             \"needs_disambiguation\": True,\n321:             \"disambiguation_checklist\": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST,\n322:             \"resources\": loaded,\n323:         }\n324: \n325:     matched_intents = []\n326:     for intent in intents:\n327:         before_count = len(loaded)\n328:         for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n329:             load_if_available(relative_path)\n330:         if len(loaded) > before_count:\n331:             matched_intents.append(intent)\n332: \n333:     text = _task_text(task)\n334:     if any(keyword in text for keyword in LOADING_LEVELS[\"ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS\"]):\n335:         for relative_path in LOADING_LEVELS[\"ON_DEMAND\"]:\n336:             load_if_available(relative_path)\n337: \n338:     if not loaded:\n339:         load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n340: \n341:     result = {\"intents\": intents, \"intent_scores\": scores, \"resources\": loaded}\n342:     if not matched_intents:\n343:         result[\"notice\"] = f\"No knowledge base found for intent(s): {', '.join(intents)}\"\n344:     return result\n345: ```\n346: \n347: ---\n348: \n349: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n350: \n351: ### Mode 1: Document Quality\n352: \n353: **Evergreen packet-ID rule**: Runtime-state docs such as README, INSTALL_GUIDE, ARCHITECTURE, SKILL, AGENTS, CLAUDE, references, feature catalogs, manual testing playbooks, and ENV_REFERENCE must not cite mutable spec or phase packet numbers. Use current feature names, file paths, commands, and source anchors instead. See [evergreen_packet_id_rule.md](./references/global/evergreen_packet_id_rule.md).\n354: \n355: Run `scripts/extract_structure.py` for structure, metrics, DQI, and checklist data. Detect document type first, then apply the right enforcement level: SKILL and command docs are strict, README docs are usability-focused, knowledge docs are moderately strict, and active spec docs are loose unless the task explicitly asks for enforcement.\n356: \n357: ### Mode 2: OpenCode Component Creation\n358: \n359: #### Skill Creation\n360: \n361: Use progressive disclosure: metadata stays in frontmatter, SKILL.md stays concise, README.md gives human orientation when needed, and deep details move to references or assets. Define scope with [skill_creation.md](./references/skill_creation.md) and use the skill templates under `assets/skill/`.\n362: \n363: #### Smart Router (Resilience Pattern)\n364: \n365: Newly scaffolded skills include the resilient smart-router skeleton by default. Fill in the skill-specific intent model, resource map, loading levels, and routing key while preserving runtime markdown discovery, `_guard_in_skill()` path sandboxing, `load_if_available()` existence checks, `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` disambiguation, and a helpful notice when keyed resources are absent. Full reference: [skill_smart_router.md](./assets/skill/skill_smart_router.md).\n366: \n367: **After packaging**: Run `extract_structure.py` on SKILL.md for final quality review.\n368: \n369: #### Agent Creation\n370: \n371: Load `agent_template.md`, define explicit tool and action permissions, include workflow/scope/anti-pattern sections, validate frontmatter, and test with examples. Agents use permission fields, not a skill-style allowed-tools array.\n372: \n373: #### Command Creation\n374: \n375: Load `command_template.md`, define name/description/triggers, write executable logic, add registry wiring where required, and test invocation.\n376: \n377: ### Mode 3: Flowchart Creation\n378: \n379: Select a pattern from `assets/flowcharts/`, build with consistent ASCII components, label decisions, and validate readability with `validate_flowchart.sh` when available.\n380: \n381: ### Mode 5: Playbook Creation\n382: \n383: Use [manual_testing_playbook_creation.md](./references/manual_testing_playbook_creation.md) and the testing playbook template. The root playbook owns package guidance; per-feature files live under numbered category folders.\n384: \n385: ### Companion Pattern: Feature Catalog Creation\n386: \n387: Use [feature_catalog_creation.md](./references/feature_catalog_creation.md) when inventorying current behavior. Keep summary inventory in the root catalog and source anchors in per-feature files.\n388: \n389: ---\n390: \n391: ## 4. RULES\n392: \n393: ### ✅ ALWAYS\n394: \n395: 1. Detect document/component type before enforcement.\n396: 2. Load the relevant template or reference before creating components.\n397: 3. Keep SKILL.md concise; move deep detail into references or assets.\n398: 4. Validate frontmatter for SKILL, agent, and command docs.\n399: 5. Validate before delivery with the appropriate sk-doc script.\n400: 6. Preserve README.md/SKILL.md casing and enforce snake_case elsewhere.\n401: 7. Keep playbooks rooted in `manual_testing_playbook.md` with per-feature files under numbered categories.\n402: \n403: ### ❌ NEVER\n404: \n405: 1. Delete original content without approval.\n406: 2. Generate llms.txt without explicit request.\n407: 3. Add a ToC outside README/research surfaces.\n408: 4. Use ambiguous agent permissions, command triggers, or playbook prompts.\n409: 5. Duplicate long guidance in SKILL.md when a reference or asset can carry it.\n410: \n411: ### ⚠️ ESCALATE IF\n412: \n413: 1. Document type, component purpose, or category boundary is unclear.\n414: 2. Critical frontmatter or structure validation fails repeatedly.\n415: 3. Brand assets, API docs, destructive test scope, or external permissions are required.\n416: 4. Flowcharts exceed practical ASCII size or need an interactive/exportable format.\n417: \n418: ---\n419: \n420: ## 5. REFERENCES\n421: \n422: The router discovers available markdown resources dynamically; do not maintain exhaustive file inventories here. Start with [quick_reference.md](./references/global/quick_reference.md), then load routed references and templates through the smart router.\n423: \n424: Primary scripts: `scripts/validate_document.py`, `scripts/extract_structure.py`, `scripts/init_skill.py`, `scripts/package_skill.py`, `scripts/quick_validate.py`, and `scripts/validate_flowchart.sh`.\n425: \n426: ---\n427: \n428: ## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n429: \n430: ### Completion Checks\n431: \n432: - Document quality: structure extracted, document type detected, critical issues addressed, validation script passes.\n433: - Skill creation: frontmatter is specific, SKILL.md is concise, resources are organized, packaging validation passes.\n434: - Agent/command creation: frontmatter is valid, permissions or triggers are explicit, examples are tested.\n435: - Flowcharts: paths are clear, decisions are labeled, spacing is readable, size limits are respected.\n436: - Install guides/playbooks/catalogs: required templates are filled, links resolve, and known validator limits are stated honestly.\n437: \n438: ### Document-Type Gates\n439: \n440: | Type      | Structure               | Content              | Required                    |\n441: | --------- | ----------------------- | -------------------- | --------------------------- |\n442: | SKILL.md  | Strict (no failures)    | High AI-friendliness | Frontmatter, WHEN/SMART/HOW/RULES/REFERENCES |\n443: | README.md | Flexible                | High AI-friendliness | Quick Start, examples       |\n444: | Knowledge | Strict (no frontmatter) | Good AI-friendliness | Numbered H2s                |\n445: \n446: ---\n447: \n448: ## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n449: \n450: This skill works with `system-spec-kit` for packet documentation and `sk-git` for commit/PR text quality. Treat spec docs as canonical continuity surfaces and use `/speckit:resume` recovery order: `handover.md -> _memory.continuity -> spec docs`.\n451: \n452: Need fast navigation? See [quick_reference.md](./references/global/quick_reference.md).\n453: \n454: ---\n455: \n456: **Remember**: This skill operates in six modes: Document Quality, Component Creation (skills/agents/commands), Flowchart Creation, Install Guide Creation, Catalog/Playbook Creation, and Benchmark Folder Creation.\n457: \n458: ---\n459: \n460: ## 8. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n461: \n462: The router discovers reference, asset, and script docs dynamically. Start with `references/global/quick_reference.md`, routed references under references/global/ and the references root, templates under assets/ root (`agent_template.md`, `command_template.md`, `feature_catalog/`, `testing_playbook/`) plus assets/readme/, assets/skill/ (`skill_md_template.md`, `skill_readme_template.md`, reference and asset scaffolds), and assets/flowcharts/, then load task-specific resources from `references/`, templates from `assets/`, and automation from `scripts/` when present.\n463: \n464: Scripts: `scripts/validate_document.py`, `scripts/extract_structure.py`, `scripts/init_skill.py`, `scripts/package_skill.py`, `scripts/quick_validate.py`, `scripts/validate_flowchart.sh`.\n465: \n466: Related skills: `system-spec-kit` for packet documentation and memory continuity, and `sk-git` for commit, PR, and release text workflows.\n\n(End of file - total 466 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: sk-doc\ndescription: \"Markdown and OpenCode component specialist: doc quality, content optimization, component scaffolds, install guides, playbooks.\"\nallowed-tools: [Bash, Edit, Glob, Grep, Read, Task, Write]\nversion: 1.5.0.0\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: sk-doc, markdown-quality, skill-creation, document-validation, ascii-flowchart, llms-txt, content-optimization, extract-structure -->\n\n# Documentation Creation Specialist - Unified Markdown & Component Management\n\nUnified specialist providing: (1) Document quality pipeline with structure enforcement and content optimization, (2) OpenCode component creation (skills, agents, commands) with scaffolding, validation and packaging, (3) ASCII flowchart creation for visualizing workflows, (4) Install guide creation for setup documentation and (5) Feature catalog and manual testing playbook creation for inventory and validation packages.\n\n**Core Principle**: Structure first, then content, then quality.\n\n**Architecture**: Scripts handle deterministic parsing/metrics. AI handles quality judgment and recommendations.\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\n### Use Case: Document Quality Management","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1780129626495,"end":1780129626508}},"id":"prt_e77fe778800152qAn0TpIyOQK6","sessionID":"ses_18801b231ffe1T23Rry15kpUZw","messageID":"msg_e77fe4fd1001FDfxxzWTB1lAMJ"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129627035,"sessionID":"ses_18801b231ffe1T23Rry15kpUZw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_02_dyX8E2cleIRILHR3k7EC3589","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: system-skill-advisor\n3: description: Routes non-trivial requests to matching skills through standalone MCP metadata and stable advisor tool ids.\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\n5: version: 0.1.0\n6: trigger_phrases:\n7:   - \"skill advisor\"\n8:   - \"gate 2 routing\"\n9:   - \"advisor_recommend\"\n10:   - \"advisor_status\"\n11:   - \"which skill should handle this\"\n12:   - \"route this request to a skill\"\n13:   - \"system skill advisor\"\n14: keywords:\n15:   - skill-routing\n16:   - gate-2\n17:   - advisor-mcp\n18:   - legacy-tool-bridge\n19:   - skill-graph\n20:   - semantic-lane\n21: intent_signals:\n22:   - \"Gate 2 skill routing\"\n23:   - \"advisor_recommend native MCP routing\"\n24:   - \"advisor_status freshness check\"\n25:   - \"which skill should handle this request\"\n26:   - \"run the skill advisor hook\"\n27: ---\n28: \n29: <!-- Keywords: system-skill-advisor, skill-advisor, advisor_recommend, advisor_status, advisor_rebuild, advisor_validate, skill_graph_scan, skill_graph_query, skill_graph_status, skill_graph_validate, skill_graph_propagate_enhances, cross-skill-edges, gate-2-routing, standalone-mcp, legacy-tool-bridge, skill-graph -->\n30: \n31: # System Skill Advisor\n32: \n33: <!-- sk-doc-template: skill_md -->\n34: \n35: Routes non-trivial user requests to the right skill through the standalone Skill Advisor MCP package.\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n40: \n41: Use this skill when the work is about skill selection, Gate 2 routing, advisor MCP tools, prompt-time skill-advisor hooks, skill graph freshness or the standalone advisor package.\n42: \n43: Activation signals:\n44: \n45: - A request asks which skill should handle a task.\n46: - A runtime hook needs a skill recommendation before execution.\n47: - An operator asks about `advisor_recommend`, `advisor_status`, `advisor_rebuild`, `advisor_validate`, `skill_graph_scan`, `skill_graph_query`, `skill_graph_status`, `skill_graph_validate` or `skill_graph_propagate_enhances`.\n48: - A packet touches the skill graph, skill metadata, advisor scorer, advisor feature catalog or manual testing playbook.\n49: - A migration step references ADR-001: `<spec-folder>`.\n50: \n51: Do not use this skill as a replacement for the recommended target skill. For example, route code implementation to `sk-code`, documentation authoring to `sk-doc`, git work to `sk-git` and MCP orchestration to `mcp-code-mode` after the advisor has made the recommendation.\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n56: \n57: This package is mandatory context for non-trivial Gate 2 routing. The live advisor scores prompts through `mk_skill_advisor`; this smart router controls which local documentation resources an agent should load while maintaining the advisor package.\n58: \n59: Routing model:\n60: \n61: ```text\n62: user prompt\n63:   |\n64:   +-- exact skill name or explicit user direction -> named skill wins\n65:   |\n66:   +-- non-trivial or ambiguous request\n67:         |\n68:         +-- advisor_recommend on mk_skill_advisor MCP\n69:         |\n70:         +-- top recommendation above confidence threshold -> invoke that skill\n71:         |\n72:         +-- ambiguous top scores -> surface top candidates and ask or route with caveat\n73: ```\n74: \n75: Resource domains:\n76: \n77: - `references/scoring/` documents scorer lanes, lane weight tuning, calibration and validation baselines.\n78: - `references/graph/` documents skill graph queries, drift reconciliation, graph extraction status and `enhances` propagation.\n79: - `references/runtime/` documents standalone MCP topology, stable tool ids, bridge policy, freshness and daemon lease behavior.\n80: - `references/config/` documents package-local database path policy.\n81: - `references/hooks/` documents prompt-time hook behavior across runtimes.\n82: - `references/decisions/` documents deferred decision records and historical rationale that still affects operators.\n83: - `feature_catalog/` documents current advisor capabilities and source-of-truth feature references.\n84: - `manual_testing_playbook/` documents deterministic operator scenarios for advisor tools, hooks, compatibility, daemon behavior and skill graph flows.\n85: - `mcp_server/` owns handlers, schemas, tools, scripts, tests, library modules and the package-local SQLite database.\n86: \n87: ### Resource loading levels\n88: \n89: | Level | When to Load | Resources |\n90: |---|---|---|\n91: | ALWAYS | Every advisor-maintenance invocation | `references/runtime/tool_ids_reference.md`, `references/runtime/standalone_mcp_shape.md` |\n92: | CONDITIONAL | Intent signals match a resource domain | Matching canonical references, feature catalog slices, or playbook scenarios |\n93: | ON_DEMAND | Explicit request or troubleshooting depth needed | Full reference folders, feature catalog families, and manual playbook categories |\n94: \n95: ### Smart router pseudocode\n96: \n97: This pseudocode captures the canonical documentation resource-loading contract. See [`references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md`](./references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md) for the actual runtime scorer mechanics.\n98: \n99: ```python\n100: from pathlib import Path\n101: \n102: SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n103: RESOURCE_BASES = (\n104:     SKILL_ROOT / \"references\",\n105:     SKILL_ROOT / \"feature_catalog\",\n106:     SKILL_ROOT / \"manual_testing_playbook\",\n107: )\n108: DEFAULT_RESOURCES = [\n109:     \"references/runtime/tool_ids_reference.md\",\n110:     \"references/runtime/standalone_mcp_shape.md\",\n111: ]\n112: \n113: INTENT_SIGNALS = {\n114:     \"SCORING\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"score\", \"scorer\", \"lane\", \"confidence\", \"calibration\", \"validate\"]},\n115:     \"GRAPH\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"skill graph\", \"graph\", \"drift\", \"query\", \"enhances\", \"propagate\"]},\n116:     \"RUNTIME\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"mcp\", \"tool id\", \"bridge\", \"standalone\", \"freshness\", \"daemon\", \"lease\"]},\n117:     \"CONFIG\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"database\", \"sqlite\", \"db path\", \"skill-graph.sqlite\"]},\n118:     \"HOOKS\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"hook\", \"prompt submit\", \"codex\", \"claude\", \"gemini\", \"devin\", \"opencode\"]},\n119:     \"DECISIONS\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"deferred\", \"decision\", \"tier d\", \"migration rationale\"]},\n120:     \"FEATURES\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"feature catalog\", \"capability\", \"current feature\"]},\n121:     \"PLAYBOOK\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"manual test\", \"playbook\", \"scenario\", \"evidence\"]},\n122: }\n123: \n124: RESOURCE_MAP = {\n125:     \"SCORING\": [\n126:         \"references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md\",\n127:         \"references/scoring/lane_weight_tuning.md\",\n128:         \"references/scoring/validation_baselines.md\",\n129:         \"feature_catalog/04--scorer-fusion/06-weights-config.md\",\n130:     ],\n131:     \"GRAPH\": [\n132:         \"references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md\",\n133:         \"references/graph/skill_graph_drift.md\",\n134:         \"references/graph/skill_graph_extraction_plan.md\",\n135:         \"references/graph/propagate_enhances.md\",\n136:     ],\n137:     \"RUNTIME\": [\n138:         \"references/runtime/standalone_mcp_shape.md\",\n139:         \"references/runtime/tool_ids_reference.md\",\n140:         \"references/runtime/legacy_tool_bridge.md\",\n141:         \"references/runtime/freshness_contract.md\",\n142:         \"references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md\",\n143:     ],\n144:     \"CONFIG\": [\n145:         \"references/config/db_path_policy.md\",\n146:     ],\n147:     \"HOOKS\": [\n148:         \"references/hooks/skill_advisor_hook.md\",\n149:         \"manual_testing_playbook/02--cli-hooks-and-plugin/005-opencode-plugin-bridge.md\",\n150:         \"manual_testing_playbook/02--cli-hooks-and-plugin/006-devin-user-prompt-submit.md\",\n151:     ],\n152:     \"DECISIONS\": [\n153:         \"references/decisions/deferred_decisions.md\",\n154:     ],\n155:     \"FEATURES\": [\n156:         \"feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md\",\n157:     ],\n158:     \"PLAYBOOK\": [\n159:         \"manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md\",\n160:     ],\n161: }\n162: \n163: UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\n164:     \"Confirm whether the request is about scoring, graph, runtime, config, hooks, decisions, feature catalog or playbooks\",\n165:     \"Confirm whether the task changes documentation only or executable advisor behavior\",\n166:     \"Provide the failing tool id, hook runtime, reference path or validation command\",\n167:     \"Confirm the verification command set before completion\",\n168: ]\n169: \n170: def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n171:     docs = []\n172:     for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n173:         if base.exists():\n174:             docs.extend(path for path in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if path.is_file())\n175:     return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n176: \n177: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n178:     resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n179:     resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n180:     if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n181:         raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routable: {relative_path}\")\n182:     return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n183: \n184: def _guard_resource_map(resource_map: dict[str, list[str]]) -> None:\n185:     for intent, resources in resource_map.items():\n186:         for relative_path in resources:\n187:             guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n188:             if guarded.startswith(\"references/\"):\n189:                 tail = guarded.removeprefix(\"references/\")\n190:                 if \"/\" not in tail and \"-\" in Path(tail).stem:\n191:                     raise ValueError(f\"RESOURCE_MAP must target canonical references, not compatibility stubs: {intent} -> {guarded}\")\n192: \n193: def _task_text(task) -> str:\n194:     fields = [\n195:         getattr(task, \"prompt\", \"\"),\n196:         getattr(task, \"intent\", \"\"),\n197:         getattr(task, \"path\", \"\"),\n198:         getattr(task, \"command\", \"\"),\n199:     ]\n200:     return \" \".join(str(field) for field in fields if field).lower()\n201: \n202: loaded = []\n203: seen = set()\n204: _guard_resource_map(RESOURCE_MAP)\n205: _guard_resource_map({\"DEFAULT\": DEFAULT_RESOURCES})\n206: inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n207: \n208: def load_if_available(relative_path: str) -> None:\n209:     guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n210:     if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n211:         load(guarded)\n212:         loaded.append(guarded)\n213:         seen.add(guarded)\n214: \n215: def score_intents(task) -> dict[str, int]:\n216:     text = _task_text(task)\n217:     scores = {}\n218:     for intent, model in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n219:         hits = sum(1 for keyword in model[\"keywords\"] if keyword in text)\n220:         if hits:\n221:             scores[intent] = hits * model[\"weight\"]\n222:     return scores\n223: \n224: for resource in DEFAULT_RESOURCES:\n225:     load_if_available(resource)\n226: \n227: scores = score_intents(task)\n228: if max(scores.values() or [0]) < 3:\n229:     return {\n230:         \"load_level\": \"UNKNOWN_FALLBACK\",\n231:         \"needs_disambiguation\": True,\n232:         \"disambiguation_checklist\": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST,\n233:         \"resources\": loaded,\n234:     }\n235: \n236: ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)\n237: top_score = ranked[0][1]\n238: selected = [intent for intent, score in ranked if top_score - score <= 1][:2]\n239: \n240: for intent in selected:\n241:     resources = RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, [])\n242:     if not resources:\n243:         return {\n244:             \"notice\": f\"No knowledge base found for advisor intent '{intent}'\",\n245:             \"resources\": loaded,\n246:         }\n247:     for resource in resources:\n248:         load_if_available(resource)\n249: \n250: return {\n251:     \"intents\": selected,\n252:     \"ambiguous\": len(selected) > 1,\n253:     \"resources\": loaded,\n254: }\n255: ```\n256: \n257: ### Fallback contract\n258: \n259: - **Low confidence:** load default runtime references, emit `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST`, and ask for the missing intent/path/tool signal.\n260: - **Ambiguous intent scores:** load the top two resource domains and disclose the ambiguity instead of picking one silently.\n261: - **Known intent with no resources:** return a \"no knowledge base found\" notice naming the missing intent.\n262: - **Advisor MCP unavailable:** fall back to Python `skill_advisor.py` shim, then to keyword matching against each skill's frontmatter `trigger_phrases`. Announce the degraded mode in the response.\n263: \n264: ### Anti-patterns\n265: \n266: - Static reference inventories that miss newly moved docs.\n267: - Loading root compatibility stubs when canonical subfolder references exist.\n268: - Compatibility stubs without `deprecated_at` and `remove_after` frontmatter, or any router target that points at a stub before the removal-window grep passes.\n269: - Raw `load(\"references/file.md\")` calls without `_guard_in_skill()`, inventory checks or duplicate suppression.\n270: - Hardcoded tool IDs in caller code. Consult the live registration in `mcp_server/tools/index.ts` and `mcp_server/tools/skill-graph-tools.ts`.\n271: \n272: ---\n273: \n274: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n275: \n276: ADR-001 locks the target shape as **Standalone Advisor MCP With Legacy Tool Bridge**.\n277: \n278: The package owns a dedicated MCP server named `mk_skill_advisor`. It registers **8 public tools plus 1 internal trusted-caller tool** (9 total). The tool ids stay stable:\n279: \n280: Public (8):\n281: \n282: - `advisor_recommend`\n283: - `advisor_rebuild`\n284: - `advisor_status`\n285: - `advisor_validate`\n286: - `skill_graph_scan`\n287: - `skill_graph_query`\n288: - `skill_graph_status`\n289: - `skill_graph_validate`\n290: \n291: Internal trusted-caller (1):\n292: \n293: - `skill_graph_propagate_enhances`, gated behind trusted-caller auth (see `references/runtime/tool_ids_reference.md` §4)\n294: \n295: The stable tool ids matter because live consumers already call them from hooks, Python compatibility shims, plugin bridges, doctor workflows, install guides and MCP clients. Server-level namespacing supplies the boundary, so callers use the standalone server without learning a new advisor vocabulary.\n296: \n297: The advisor implementation, skill-graph library and package-local database now live under this skill package, while memory remains focused on memory tools.\n298: \n299: ---\n300: \n301: ## 4. RULES\n302: \n303: Always:\n304: \n305: - Treat ADR-001 as the source of truth for standalone MCP topology and bridge behavior.\n306: - Keep the advisor database under `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/database/`.\n307: - Keep public advisor and skill graph tool ids stable unless a later ADR explicitly changes them.\n308: - Preserve prompt-safety boundaries. Advisor metadata and lane attribution must not echo raw prompt text.\n309: - Keep `lib/skill-graph/` package-local to `system-skill-advisor`.\n310: \n311: Never:\n312: \n313: - Store `skill-graph.sqlite` under `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/database/` after the runtime move.\n314: - Let both memory and advisor MCP servers write the same advisor SQLite database.\n315: - Rename `advisor_*` or `skill_graph_*` public tools as part of documentation work.\n316: - Move `lib/skill-graph/` during a doc-only pass.\n317: \n318: Escalate if:\n319: \n320: - A caller requires renamed public tools.\n321: - The standalone advisor cannot build without a broader shared-runtime extraction.\n322: - Any migration step would create competing writers for `skill-graph.sqlite`.\n323: \n324: ---\n325: \n326: ## 5. REFERENCES\n327: \n328: Primary contract:\n329: \n330: - ADR-001: internal design notes\n331: - Extraction survey: internal design notes\n332: - Standalone MCP discussion: internal design notes\n333: \n334: Package references:\n335: \n336: - `references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md` — lane attribution, fusion and confidence calibration.\n337: - `references/scoring/lane_weight_tuning.md` — measured lane-weight change workflow.\n338: - `references/scoring/validation_baselines.md` — `advisor_validate` baselines and troubleshooting.\n339: - `references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md` — worked `skill_graph_query` examples.\n340: - `references/graph/skill_graph_drift.md` — detect and reconcile SQLite drift from source files.\n341: - `references/graph/skill_graph_extraction_plan.md` — extraction history and completion record.\n342: - `references/graph/propagate_enhances.md` — internal `enhances` propagation contract.\n343: - `references/runtime/standalone_mcp_shape.md` — standalone MCP topology.\n344: - `references/runtime/tool_ids_reference.md` — stable public and internal tool ids.\n345: - `references/runtime/legacy_tool_bridge.md` — compatibility bridge policy.\n346: - `references/runtime/freshness_contract.md` — trust-state vocabulary and caller obligations.\n347: - `references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md` — single-writer daemon lease behavior.\n348: - `references/config/db_path_policy.md` — package-local SQLite path policy.\n349: - `references/hooks/skill_advisor_hook.md` — prompt-time hook behavior.\n350: - `references/decisions/deferred_decisions.md` — Tier D decision records (F4 Devin hooks, F6 deprecation banners).\n351: - `ARCHITECTURE.md`\n352: - `mcp_server/README.md`\n353: - `mcp_server/tools/README.md`\n354: \n355: ---\n356: \n357: ## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n358: \n359: This skill is healthy when:\n360: \n361: - `SKILL.md` frontmatter and `graph-metadata.json` parse cleanly.\n362: - Skill discovery sees `system-skill-advisor` as a first-class critical system skill.\n363: - Advisor routing requests resolve to this package without displacing target execution skills such as `sk-code`, `sk-doc` or `system-spec-kit`.\n364: - `advisor_*` and `skill_graph_*` public ids remain documented as stable.\n365: - The package-local database path is documented consistently.\n366: \n367: ---\n368: \n369: ## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n370: \n371: Current package state:\n372: \n373: - `mk_skill_advisor` is registered as a standalone MCP server.\n374: - Advisor handlers, schemas, tools, scripts, tests, docs and database path ownership live under this package.\n375: - `skill_graph_*` MCP handlers and tool descriptors live under this package.\n376: - `lib/skill-graph/` database/query logic is fully migrated to `system-skill-advisor` (extraction complete).\n377: \n378: Expected consumers:\n379: \n380: - Prompt-time hooks for Claude, Codex, Gemini and OpenCode.\n381: - MCP clients that call `advisor_recommend`, `advisor_status`, `advisor_rebuild`, `advisor_validate`, `skill_graph_scan`, `skill_graph_query`, `skill_graph_status`, `skill_graph_validate` or `skill_graph_propagate_enhances`.\n382: - Doctor workflows that validate advisor health and rebuild state.\n383: - Skill graph indexers and routing accuracy checks.\n384: \n385: ---\n386: \n387: ## 8. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n388: \n389: Related skills:\n390: \n391: - `system-spec-kit` owns spec folders, memory, validation and packet governance.\n392: - `sk-doc` owns skill documentation, feature catalogs, install guides and playbooks.\n393: - `sk-code` owns implementation once routing selects a code surface.\n394: - `mcp-code-mode` owns external MCP orchestration workflows.\n395: - `system-code-graph` owns structural code indexing, graph readiness and impact-analysis workflows.\n396: \n397: The advisor should recommend these skills. It should not absorb their implementation rules.\n\n(End of file - total 397 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: system-skill-advisor\ndescription: Routes non-trivial requests to matching skills through standalone MCP metadata and stable advisor tool ids.\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\nversion: 0.1.0\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill advisor\"\n  - \"gate 2 routing\"\n  - \"advisor_recommend\"\n  - \"advisor_status\"\n  - \"which skill should handle this\"\n  - \"route this request to a skill\"\n  - \"system skill advisor\"\nkeywords:\n  - skill-routing\n  - gate-2\n  - advisor-mcp\n  - legacy-tool-bridge\n  - skill-graph\n  - semantic-lane","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1780129627022,"end":1780129627034}},"id":"prt_e77fe799e0017qdZ2dCEkP9OVF","sessionID":"ses_18801b231ffe1T23Rry15kpUZw","messageID":"msg_e77fe4fd1001FDfxxzWTB1lAMJ"}}
